Principal Investigator: Renee Fabus, Ph.D., CCC-SLP, TSHH

column2: The information in this form is being used to seek your consent for a research study. Being in the study is voluntary, it is up to you.

This research is being done to find out the extent to which parents’ beliefs relate to whether or not they seek intervention services for their children with disabilities. Participation will last up to 15 minutes.

column1: Study procedures for this research are:

column2: Accessing the survey via website address link
Reading through this consent form and agreeing to participate
Completing the online survey through Qualtrics
The most likely risks to you of the research are: There is minimal risk for you to complete this survey. *Please see the RISKS and DISCOMFORTS section for a complete list of expected side effects*

The most likely benefits to you of the research are: There are no direct benefits, however, participating in this study will benefit the field of special education/Speech-Language Pathology in learning further about parent’s beliefs in relation to decisions regarding their child with disability.
The following risks/discomforts may occur as a result of you being in this study: There are no foreseeable risks or discomforts associated with participation in this research.
If you decide to not be in the research, your choices (if any) are: If you decide not to participate in this research, you do not need to submit the survey, it can be terminated at any time.
You are being asked to be a volunteer in a research study.

column1: The purpose of this study is to investigate how the beliefs of culturally, racially, and ethnically diverse parents impact their decisions in getting intervention services for their child with disabilities. You have been invited to participate in this study as you are a parent of a child or an expecting parent. There has been little research on parental beliefs in correlation with intervention services, we wish to further explore the role beliefs has on a parent’s decision to seek services for their child. Investigators expect to survey at least 80 participants for this study. The survey will be sent out via online groups, social media platforms, and posted at public libraries.
If you decide to be in this study, your part will involve:

column2: Completing an online survey that will be available via a Qualtrics website link with 45 questions, which should take no longer than 15 minutes.

column1: Identifiers will not be collected along with your survey responses. All survey responses will remain anonymous and can be terminated at any time.
There are no foreseeable risks or discomforts associated with your participation in this study.
There is no direct benefit expected as a result of you being in this study.
There will be no direct compensation for your participation in this study.

All the information we get about you will not be linked to you at all. We will do this by not writing down your name or anything else that could link you in any way to the answers you give us for our study. All the study data we obtain from you will remain confidential and secure. If any papers or presentations are given about this research, your name will not be used.
There are no foreseeable costs associated with participating in this study.
Your alternative to being in this study is to no participate
There are no foreseeable injuries in participating in this study.
YOU RIGHTS AS A RESEARCH SUBJECT
Your participation in this study is voluntary. You do not have to be in this study if you do not want to be.
You have the right to change your mind and leave the study at any time without giving any reason, and without penalty.
Any new information that may make you change your mind about being in this study will be given to you.
You can print a copy of this consent form to keep.
You do not lose any of your legal rights by agreeing to participate in this study.
QUESTIONS ABOUT THE STUDY OR YOUR RIGHTS AS A RESEARCH SUBJECT

column2: If you have any questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, you may contact Dr. Renee Fabus by phone at (631) 638-0502.

If you have any questions about your rights as a research subject or if you would like to obtain information or offer input, you may contact the Stony Brook University Research Subject Advocate, Ms. Lu-Ann Kozlowski, BSN, RN, (631) 632-9036, OR by e-mail, lu-ann.kozlowski@stonybrook.edu

Visit Stony Brook University’s Community Outreach page, http://research.stonybrook.edu/orc/community.shtml#overview-of-volunteering-in-research for more information about participating in research, frequently asked questions, and an opportunity to provide feedback, comments, or ask questions related to your experience as a research subject.
